WEBVTT

00:01.154 --> 00:02.756
Well, good morning to you, church family.

00:03.998 --> 00:09.565
We have been walking verse by verse through second Corinthians chapter 10.

00:10.366 --> 00:12.648
We're really beginning with second Corinthians chapter one.

00:12.689 --> 00:15.452
And we've made our way now to chapter 10.

00:16.073 --> 00:26.766
And we're looking at passages here that normally you probably would never hear a sermon on, but oftentimes in the most unsuspecting of places you find the greatest treasures.

00:28.288 --> 00:29.810
I want to take you back to Gideon.

00:30.530 --> 00:39.607
In the Old Testament, when all of the people along with Gideon rose very early in the morning, the battle lines had been drawn.

00:39.667 --> 00:52.050
The Gideonites, as you remember, had been harassing God's people for the last seven years, and they drove Israel to retreat into the local mountains and caves.

00:52.642 --> 01:01.551
And in the midst of that, God called up one of the most unlikely of men, and he promised to be with him to deliver God's people through him.

01:01.591 --> 01:05.895
And he called Gideon, quote, a mighty man of valor.

01:05.955 --> 01:16.746
Gideon presented an offering before the Lord, and the Lord strengthened him, and the Lord assured him through a sign of his presence.

01:17.126 --> 01:21.010
And Gideon went throughout the land, and he crushed their idol.

01:21.890 --> 01:26.636
And the people then were waiting for their marching orders to move forward.

01:27.637 --> 01:35.227
And in the midst of that, the Lord revealed one of the most bizarre battle tactics ever known to man.

01:36.188 --> 01:50.386
In Judges 7, chapter seven, verse two we read, the Lord said to Gideon, the people with you are too many for me to give the Midianites into their hand, the less to Israel,

01:50.594 --> 01:57.205
boast over me saying, my own hand has saved me.

01:57.265 --> 02:06.119
And so the Lord reduced their number 32,000 already, not a mighty number before such a formidable army.

02:06.519 --> 02:18.098
And he began to whittle it down until they only had 300 people so that there is no way they could boast of their own flesh of any victory.

02:19.298 --> 02:21.842
in 1 Kings chapter 20 verse 11.

02:23.064 --> 02:26.350
The king of Syria gathered his army together.

02:26.410 --> 02:39.231
He recruited 32 other kings and he again threatened to harass and plunder Israel to take their wealth, to take their wives, to take their children.

02:39.291 --> 02:46.162
And before his threats, which were unprovoked, we read in 1 Kings 20,

02:46.626 --> 02:59.906
verse 11, and the king of Israel answered, tell him, let not the one who straps on his armor boast himself as he who takes it off.

03:01.188 --> 03:04.633
In other words, we have smack talk in the ancient world.

03:05.755 --> 03:15.570
You talk a big game, but if you're going to boast, why don't you boast after you finish the job not before?

03:15.714 --> 03:25.348
Emma's eye, a king of Judah, was warned in 2 Chronicles 25, 19, quote, your heart has lifted you up in boastfulness.

03:25.849 --> 03:27.311
Stay home.

03:28.533 --> 03:29.955
And he refused to stay home.

03:31.137 --> 03:36.265
And he suffered a slaughter as a result of his boastfulness.

03:37.447 --> 03:39.109
Men would boast against Moses.

03:39.389 --> 03:45.138
And as a result, God would swallow them up in judgment, literally in the earth.

03:46.306 --> 03:48.388
In the New Testament, King Herod boasted.

03:48.428 --> 04:04.106
The people began to treat him like a God, and King Herod received that as worship from the people, and the Bible says that an angel struck him down for refusing to give glory to God, and he was eaten by worms.

04:05.608 --> 04:11.314
Friends, the Bible is filled with boasting, both good boasting and bad boasting.

04:12.226 --> 04:18.316
And I believe the reason is because man naturally is a very boastful creature.

04:18.356 --> 04:27.892
In Second Corinthians 10, scripture gives us a prescription for how we should boast, how we should not boast.

04:27.912 --> 04:32.179
But we know that we live in a very boastful world.

04:33.220 --> 04:34.883
Have you been on social media lately?

04:34.923 --> 04:39.090
Filled with pictures and posts of

04:39.330 --> 04:42.874
I'm not bragging, but we all really know that you're bragging.

04:44.335 --> 04:45.596
What about public leaders?

04:46.757 --> 04:50.321
Do public leaders love to boast of themselves?

04:51.502 --> 05:01.832
The truth is that in one way or another, we all love to boast of what we think we are, of what we think we've accomplished.

05:01.852 --> 05:07.538
And I believe we live in a world where many people, and if we're not careful, including us,

05:07.970 --> 05:10.654
are very prone to being insecure.

05:10.714 --> 05:23.595
And so if we're not careful, we will begin to present ourselves in a boastful way to try to make up on the outside for what we know is lacking on the inside.

05:24.497 --> 05:31.989
The idea of boasting, I believe stems from insecurity from pride, obviously from sin in the most negative way.

05:32.029 --> 05:35.314
And it's a

05:35.554 --> 05:37.777
It's an attempt to promote oneself.

05:38.578 --> 05:45.967
Maybe who you think you are, maybe what you have, maybe thinking what you can do or what you have done.

05:45.987 --> 05:53.436
I want to look this morning at the title of my sermon, which is the measure of a man and his ministry.

05:54.678 --> 05:57.361
How should we consider ourselves?

05:57.561 --> 05:59.744
How should we or should we not boast?

06:00.124 --> 06:04.690
How should we consider ourselves before God and before one another?

06:05.186 --> 06:06.568
How do we measure ourselves?

06:06.608 --> 06:09.092
Should we compare ourselves one with another?

06:09.392 --> 06:11.395
Should we ever put ourselves forward?

06:12.277 --> 06:23.073
Is it possible that we can be plagued with the fear of man and a desire incessantly to please other people and make them think that we are more than in fact, we truly are?

06:23.113 --> 06:27.399
Is there a standard, a measuring stick?

06:27.480 --> 06:34.450
Is there a metric by which we may properly consider ourselves and measure faithful ministry?

06:35.490 --> 06:42.337
Look with me in 2 Corinthians chapter 10, false teachers are continuing to ravage this church in Corinth.

06:42.757 --> 06:51.485
Even as many have repented, there's a remaining faction that have not repented in the church, and there are false teachers at the heart of this.

06:52.406 --> 07:04.498
If you look with me in verses 7 through 11, we saw last Sunday that it appears Paul was accused of boasting of being overconfident, maybe even as being

07:04.738 --> 07:11.345
authoritarian, a heavy handed towards the church, seeking to frighten and even destroy them.

07:11.385 --> 07:19.854
And Paul laid out what I have described as five aspects of authority that he displays in the church.

07:19.874 --> 07:20.935
Look with me in verse seven.

07:22.137 --> 07:25.780
We see authority that's securing Christ and not selfish and motive.

07:27.022 --> 07:31.026
We saw in verse eight, number two, authority that's assertive and not arrogant.

07:31.874 --> 07:37.120
Thirdly, we saw in verse eight, authority that builds up and doesn't tear down.

07:37.140 --> 07:45.150
We saw in verses nine and 10, authority that puts terror in your enemies and loving respect in your people.

07:46.472 --> 07:52.519
And finally, number five, verse 11, we saw last week authority that is spoken and acted on.

07:52.559 --> 08:01.330
And so Paul is asserting his authority before the church so that they would respond faithfully and humbly before the Lord.

08:02.402 --> 08:10.112
We continue now this morning in 2 Corinthians 10 verses 12 through 18 as we see the measure of a man and his ministry.

08:11.313 --> 08:18.742
I want you to know, first of all, very clearly, number one, we don't measure ourselves by those who commend themselves.

08:20.044 --> 08:24.670
We don't measure ourselves by those who commend themselves.

08:25.971 --> 08:28.855
Do you know people who love to commend themselves?

08:30.016 --> 08:31.538
Are you one of such people?

08:32.802 --> 08:40.955
Look within verse 12 and we're going to we're going to camp out here just for a little bit.

08:42.097 --> 08:52.974
Paul says not that we desire to classify or compare ourselves with some of those who are commending themselves.

08:54.496 --> 09:00.626
But when they measure themselves by one another and compare themselves with one another,

09:01.602 --> 09:03.966
they are without understanding.

09:04.006 --> 09:21.874
Paul frames this entire section that we're in in verse 12 and then circling back around in verse 18 with the word and idea of commending how we are to commend ourselves and how we are not to commend ourselves and how God will commend us.

09:22.818 --> 09:44.724
If you look with me in verse 12, Paul says that he, possibly including his ministry team, refused to classify or to put themselves in the same category as, or to compare themselves with these hucksters who have defrauded the church and are winsomely gaining influence over the people of God.

09:44.764 --> 09:50.130
Some translations have it this way, we don't dare.

09:50.530 --> 10:00.345
We wouldn't have the audacity, a word that Paul uses in this letter to do such a thing, to classify ourselves with the boastful.

10:01.406 --> 10:06.474
Are the King James says, we don't dare put ourselves in their number or class.

10:08.217 --> 10:19.634
It seems very clear from the previous verses that we've already seen that the false teachers and the church at large were comparing Paul's ministry to that of the false teachers.

10:20.354 --> 10:27.603
And many are concluding that Paul simply doesn't measure up to these guys that they have no business trusting.

10:28.684 --> 10:39.818
We saw just last Sunday how the church, at least many within it, seemed to find Paul compared to them lacking in a very persuasive speech.

10:41.119 --> 10:45.325
They speak so much more eloquently, so much more persuasively.

10:45.605 --> 10:49.810
They find Paul lacking in a very powerful persona

10:50.658 --> 10:55.824
And Paul admits, I come to you in weakness, but by the power of God.

10:57.485 --> 11:01.910
Paul says, there's no way I would ever compare myself with such deceitful hucksters.

11:02.210 --> 11:05.434
Look with me in your Bibles with some of those who are committing themselves.

11:05.754 --> 11:08.557
The Geneva translation says, praise themselves.

11:10.179 --> 11:14.143
So they're demeaning Paul for his speech and for his presence.

11:14.604 --> 11:20.530
In chapter 11, they demean him for refusing to accept support from the church.

11:21.026 --> 11:23.209
which they believe would legitimize his ministry.

11:24.131 --> 11:32.924
In chapter 11, verse 22, they seem to demean him for his family lying, for his descendants from the family that he's come from.

11:33.305 --> 11:45.344
In chapter 12, maybe they demean him for his lack of mystical spiritual experiences, maybe even for what they perceived to be his lack of mighty miracles in chapter 12, verse 12.

11:47.026 --> 11:49.490
Scholars say that it was a very common tactic

11:50.626 --> 11:55.454
for teachers of the day to try to win followers to themselves.

11:56.635 --> 12:01.082
And the way they would often do it is they would compare themselves to other teachers.

12:02.585 --> 12:03.767
Is this a tactic today?

12:03.787 --> 12:18.610
Highlighting the absolute worst in other teachers, minimizing the worst in themselves and then walking all over others in order to get to the top of the ladder themselves.

12:19.554 --> 12:23.219
Turn with me in your Bibles to 1 Corinthians chapter 4.

12:26.363 --> 12:38.180
In 1 Corinthians chapter 4, Paul already addresses this idea of comparing and commending, not going beyond one's proper limits, he'll later say.

12:38.200 --> 12:48.434
In 1 Corinthians chapter 4, as we've seen years ago, walking through this passage, Paul bears his soul before the church,

12:48.578 --> 12:50.119
and honesty before God.

12:50.160 --> 12:54.624
And he says in verse one, for I am not aware of anything against myself.

12:55.825 --> 12:57.166
By the way, what a statement.

12:58.087 --> 13:00.209
Are you aware of anything against yourself?

13:01.691 --> 13:02.071
I am.

13:03.672 --> 13:09.258
Can anyone say before God, I am not aware of anything before myself, against myself.

13:11.560 --> 13:17.906
But I am not even then thereby acquitted.

13:18.274 --> 13:20.457
Paul is not perfect, he's blameless.

13:20.537 --> 13:22.740
He's seeking to walk in holiness and repentance.

13:24.563 --> 13:26.105
It is the Lord who judges me.

13:26.165 --> 13:41.548
And he says in verse five, therefore do not pronounce judgment before the time, before the Lord comes, who will bring to light the things now hidden in darkness and will disclose the purposes of the heart.

13:42.729 --> 13:46.034
Be careful judging about by its cover.

13:46.530 --> 13:51.636
Be careful against judging a person or a matter too quickly.

13:53.338 --> 14:02.228
He says, then each one, when God brings all things to life, we'll receive His commendation from God.

14:02.248 --> 14:14.962
I have applied all these things to myself, and He mentions a policy for your benefit, brothers, that you may learn by us not to go beyond what is written.

14:15.586 --> 14:24.499
that none of you be puffed up, be arrogant, boastful in favor of one against another.

14:24.539 --> 14:28.685
It's a very sobering proper assessment.

14:29.205 --> 14:43.666
It's the person who comes before the Lord in their prayers this, Psalm 139, Lord, would you search me even as I search myself, being honest before God about the state of my soul,

14:44.162 --> 14:55.318
And Psalm 19, Lord, would you make it so that the words of my mouth and the meditations of my heart are pleasing in your sight?

14:56.439 --> 14:57.641
Lord, would you forgive me?

14:57.701 --> 14:59.724
Would you help me?

14:59.764 --> 15:01.747
Would you lead me?

15:01.767 --> 15:05.011
Is that the attitude of your heart this morning?

15:06.193 --> 15:12.722
And now, Lord, my conscience is cleansed before you when we pray the prayer of confession.

15:12.930 --> 15:15.673
And then offer a sense of absolution.

15:15.734 --> 15:21.941
We are trusting in the merits of Christ to cleanse us and give us assurance of his pardon.

15:22.242 --> 15:26.607
So Lord, my conscience is clean before you because of the blood of Jesus Christ.

15:27.729 --> 15:31.794
But even then, God alone is the judge.

15:32.114 --> 15:33.376
He knows all things.

15:33.436 --> 15:39.784
So we are very careful about judging a matter too quickly, jumping to conclusions.

15:40.925 --> 15:41.746
What about you?

15:42.658 --> 15:47.884
Have you ever been a little hasty to jump to conclusions about a particular matter?

15:49.046 --> 15:55.053
And then you found yourself like Peter, the disciple, who constantly had to put his foot in his mouth.

15:56.675 --> 15:58.037
I can certainly relate to that.

15:58.057 --> 16:04.725
And God will bring delight in the true motivations of all and he will commend each one.

16:04.765 --> 16:12.594
As it pertains to leaders in the church, which is the matter in 2 Corinthians, 1 Timothy 5 says, be very careful.

16:13.666 --> 16:16.710
Lord knows we've made this mistake as a church in years past.

16:16.750 --> 16:21.876
Be very careful because for some people their sins go before them.

16:21.936 --> 16:25.220
In other words, they wear their sin on their sleeve.

16:25.340 --> 16:28.163
It's very evident.

16:28.183 --> 16:32.669
But for other people, Paul warns Timothy, they follow behind them.

16:32.689 --> 16:41.019
It takes more time to see the character tested, to see what's in the heart come squeezed out of the hands.

16:41.399 --> 16:43.602
For some people, it takes more time.

16:44.450 --> 17:01.414
So don't lay hands on a man hastily, which is exactly the problem in 2 Corinthians, whether they lay hands on them or not is not the matter, but the matter that they have given their influence and heart, submitting to those whom they should not have.

17:02.656 --> 17:06.341
Paul says in 1 Corinthians 8 that food will not commend us to God.

17:07.723 --> 17:09.746
He says in 1 Corinthians 11,

17:09.890 --> 17:16.817
They commends the church for some things, but the way they're handling themselves at the Lord's Supper is not one of them.

17:18.538 --> 17:20.080
Look with me in 2 Corinthians.

17:20.760 --> 17:26.586
We see Paul saying in 2 Corinthians chapter three, verse one, I'm your father in the faith.

17:26.806 --> 17:28.708
Don't make me commend myself to you.

17:29.989 --> 17:35.034
Presenting letters of recommendation, you know me better than that.

17:36.315 --> 17:39.698
He says in chapter 13, verse 12, I should not

17:40.066 --> 17:41.708
have to commend myself to you.

17:42.028 --> 17:43.931
I should be commended by you."

17:43.971 --> 17:49.517
And so Paul says in 2 Corinthians, I'm not boasting of myself.

17:49.637 --> 17:58.608
I'm trying to give you reason to boast in me because my divine calling and the fruitfulness of my ministry should be clear before you.

17:58.628 --> 18:06.738
He says in chapter 6 verse 4 that if we are to commend ourselves, it is with endurance through suffering

18:06.850 --> 18:08.012
on your behalf.

18:08.292 --> 18:13.960
That is the only way I will put myself forward or commend myself.

18:16.183 --> 18:22.893
These men, if you'll look with me in 2 Corinthians 10, 12 are measuring themselves against the metric of one another.

18:22.933 --> 18:29.302
They're comparing themselves with one another and Paul says, this is a fool's errand.

18:30.844 --> 18:32.466
The King James version says,

18:32.610 --> 18:34.693
translation says they are not wise.

18:35.033 --> 18:38.959
The new American standard says they are without understanding.

18:39.019 --> 18:43.465
They refuse to measure themselves before God.

18:43.505 --> 18:52.877
So they measure themselves according to the standard of one another rather than the plum line of God's word.

18:54.079 --> 18:56.342
All it does is bolster their own pride.

18:57.924 --> 19:02.130
And friends, I believe that we can be so

19:02.594 --> 19:06.478
We must be so careful not to do the same ourselves.

19:08.059 --> 19:21.252
I believe the idea here is that regardless of how big they cock their feathers out underneath, all they are is small little birds making a lot of noise.

19:22.293 --> 19:26.618
They may be full of noise, but they are filled with dead men's bones.

19:26.958 --> 19:29.320
Jesus said whitewash tunes.

19:30.221 --> 19:31.122
That's what they are.

19:33.602 --> 19:45.037
All we're seeing in this matter in the Church of Corinth, I believe, is one of the most disgusting things that you will ever find in a church.

19:46.238 --> 19:49.322
It's a sick game of spiritual one-upmanship.

19:50.564 --> 20:01.938
It's the idea that they love to sing their own praises and they're parading themselves to try to figure out who is going to get the most spiritual person of the year award.

20:03.138 --> 20:06.882
And it's all of a sod, it's all fake, there's nothing genuine.

20:07.243 --> 20:13.990
And I am telling you, I have seen that and I have absolutely no interest in it in our church.

20:16.753 --> 20:21.158
They feel mighty about themselves, but only as they compare themselves with one another.

20:21.519 --> 20:31.570
Maybe they're flattering themselves because immediately the tendency is to find other people who look less than you so that your pride can be increased through it.

20:32.578 --> 20:41.329
Or maybe you see other people who in some area are another look greater than you are growing more than you are.

20:41.389 --> 20:48.038
So it provokes envy and jealousy of another person in comparison.

20:50.081 --> 20:54.927
Brothers and sisters, we all have clay feet and clay chests.

20:56.409 --> 21:00.274
And before God, we are all prone to the same things.

21:01.346 --> 21:06.613
And I believe what these false teachers have is what we would often call little man syndrome.

21:08.075 --> 21:13.081
They are small on the inside, so they try to make themselves big on the outside.

21:13.362 --> 21:23.074
Listen to Proverbs 27, two, let another praise you and not your own mouth, a stranger and not your own lips.

21:23.094 --> 21:28.882
Proverbs 26, 12, do you see a man who is wise in his own eyes?

21:29.666 --> 21:32.569
There is more hope for a fool than for him.

21:32.589 --> 21:41.399
How many of you would be willing to confess that you thought when you were growing up, your parents were the dumbest people in the world?

21:43.121 --> 21:55.494
And then as you get in your late teens and in your twenties, you think, I am so wise if the rest of the world would just listen to me and do what I say, this would be a much better place.

21:56.856 --> 21:59.058
And so if we could have had

21:59.266 --> 22:05.774
social media back then, if I could start a book tour, if everyone would just listen to my voice.

22:07.937 --> 22:20.672
And then how many of you get a little older and realize you really weren't so smart like you thought you were and your parents were a little bit more smarter than you thought they were.

22:21.733 --> 22:28.882
And you were not so wise in the eyes of others as you were in your own eyes.

22:29.954 --> 22:40.806
Sit down young man, sit down young lady, learn from the wisdom of others, and don't be so eager to parade yourselves.

22:40.866 --> 22:42.648
And that goes for you older people too.

22:44.330 --> 22:59.186
Comparison is nothing but a very small and corrupt game of jealousy, of insecurity, of coveting, of envy, and of pride.

23:00.322 --> 23:10.277
And I believe it's more pronounced on the surface at least in our day than maybe we have experienced in a long time.

23:11.559 --> 23:18.229
Social media is a hotbed for this fool's errand of comparison.

23:19.451 --> 23:25.360
You ever looked at pictures of other people's families and buddy, they have it all together.

23:25.440 --> 23:29.106
Everybody is in their place looking sharp and smiling.

23:30.626 --> 23:43.045
And you have no clue what they endured right before and right after that one snapshot that they selectively pulled out as a frame of their life to put forward.

23:44.628 --> 23:47.873
Does it feel like everybody lives in a bigger house than you do?

23:47.893 --> 23:56.146
Does it feel like as you hit marks April and May that everyone is at the beach except for you?

23:56.834 --> 23:59.278
Everybody has a nicer car than you.

23:59.338 --> 24:07.510
Everyone's at the mountains, but you, everyone has a godly husband, except for you.

24:07.591 --> 24:25.458
Everyone has a sweet, submissive wife, but you, everyone has great children, but you, anyone susceptible to this gang, thank you for your honest hands and to the rest of you, you are liars and you know it.

24:28.386 --> 24:57.554
And what a timely passage right here to remind us that this is a very small and corrupt game to compare myself with other people on such trivial matters of the way I look and dress, comparing how much money I make or don't make, how much I have, what kind of job I have or don't have, how life has turned out, whatever,

24:57.890 --> 25:08.246
The matter is, it provokes jealousy in some, it provokes pride in others, and it's exactly what we see in Psalm 73.

25:08.286 --> 25:19.064
The psalmist says, God, why is it that the bad guys always win and the good guys always lose?

25:20.305 --> 25:25.714
The people who despise your name get promotions at work and have it all together.

25:26.498 --> 25:31.446
And the people who faithfully serve you, barely keep their head above water.

25:32.407 --> 25:32.948
Lord, why?

25:34.971 --> 25:44.186
And the psalmist does not get a single answer to his question, but he does conclude in Psalm 73, I am nothing but a wild beast.

25:45.488 --> 25:54.322
What's wrong with me, he says, comparing myself, judging matters too soon, not understanding the whole,

25:55.042 --> 26:00.610
He says, I have the Lord and the Lord is with me and his covenant promises are mine forever.

26:00.971 --> 26:02.593
Why would I even think like that?

26:05.217 --> 26:06.559
Why would I even think like that?

26:06.599 --> 26:17.234
Look with me in second Corinthians 10, 12, I believe the more specific point in this passage is that the measure of a man in a faithful ministry

26:17.442 --> 26:34.551
is not comparison with self-appointed Charismatics who put themselves forward, but it's using the standard of God's word to evaluate the calling and the character of a person and to see the fruitfulness from a ministry that follows over an extended period of time.

26:35.853 --> 26:43.186
And so we need to be careful the metrics that we use to evaluate what it means to know and love Christ and be godly.

26:43.874 --> 26:51.845
We need to be careful the metrics that we use to judge what it means for us to be a faithful, healthy church.

26:53.727 --> 26:58.393
Galatians five gives us some pretty good metrics.

26:58.413 --> 27:07.846
When it lays out the fruit or the evidences of the flesh versus the fruit of the Holy Spirit in a person's life in a church.

27:09.648 --> 27:11.090
Look with me in one more passage.

27:11.110 --> 27:13.874
Turn with me, if you will, to James chapter three.

27:15.650 --> 27:36.936
The person who begins to get called up into this game of comparison, not only church leaders, but even church members, to try to impress one another with a false pretense of spirituality, the Bible says this is a person who is without understanding.

27:39.219 --> 27:45.426
Look with me in James chapter three, verse 13. Who is wise and what?

27:46.626 --> 27:47.107
Are you there?

27:48.528 --> 27:50.912
Who is wise in understanding among you?

27:52.353 --> 27:53.395
So what does it mean?

27:54.076 --> 27:58.421
And what does it look like to have understanding as a Christian and as a church?

27:59.843 --> 28:03.408
